1. c4 (1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nc6) 1... e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. Qc2 (6. e3 Bf5 7. Qf3) 6... Bd6 { The Kassa Korley variation! This sideline of the Queen's Gambit Declined, has gotten some popularity recently due to some specatular games from IM Kassa Korley } (6... h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nxd5 Qxd4 { is okay for black, but I was couldn't quite figure out the evaluation during the game, so I decided to delay h6 }) 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bh4 Re8 10. Nf3 (10. Nge2 a5 11. O-O (11. h3 Na6 12. a3 Nc7 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gc7e6,Ge6g5] }) 11... Bxh2+) 10... Be6 11. O-O (11. Ne5?! c5) 11... Nbd7 12. a3 a5 13. Rab1 { [%csl Gb8][%cal Gd8b8] } 13... Qb8 14. Bg3 b5 { This creates a potentially weak backward c-pawn, but has the later positional idea of a4 and Nb6-c4, establishing a nice outpost } (14... Bxg3 15. hxg3 Bg4 { Engine suggestion }) 15. Ne2 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gc2c6] } 15... Bxg3 16. hxg3 Qd6 17. Rfc1 Rec8 18. Nf4 a4 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 (19... fxe6) 20. Bf5 Qd6 21. Ne5 Ra7 22. Qc3 Rac7 23. Qb4 Qxb4 24. axb4 Nxe5 25. dxe5 (25. Bxc8 Nd3 { [%csl Rc1,Rb4,Rc8] } 26. Rc3 Nxb4 27. Bf5) 25... Nd7 26. b3 axb3 27. Rxb3 { [%csl Rd7,Rc7,Rc8,Rc3][%cal Gf5c8,Gc8c6,Gb3c3] } 27... Kf8 28. f4 { [%csl Ge5,Gf4,Gg3,Ge3][%cal Gf4g3] } 28... Ke7 29. Rbc3 g6 30. Bh3 f6? { This move will haunt me for the rest of my life. I should have listened to Ben Finegold. } 31. exf6+ Kxf6 (31... Kd6 32. e4! { What I had initially overlooked } 32... dxe4 33. Rd1#) 32. Bxd7 Rxd7 33. Rxc6+ Rxc6 34. Rxc6+ Kf5 35. Kf2 { [%csl Rb5,Rd5,Rd7,Gc6] } 35... g5 36. Rxh6 d4 37. Rh5 { [%cal Gf5g6,Gf5f6,Gf5e6] } (37. Rb6 { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb6b5] } 37... Rd5 38. Kf3 g4+ 39. Ke2 dxe3 40. Kxe3 Rd3+ { my genius idea that still doesn't work. } 41. Ke2 (41. Kxd3) (41. Kf2)) 37... Ke4 38. exd4 Rxd4 39. Rxg5 Rxb4 40. Re5+ Kd4 41. g4 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Gg4g8,Rb4b5] } 41... Kc3 { [%csl Gb2,Gb3,Gb4,Rf4][%cal Gb4f4] } 42. g5 { I was surprised when he played this move... why would he let me take a free pawn with check? 